### Good Code Snippet

```java
// Good code snippet with input validation
public void handleUserInput(String input) {
    // Validate input to prevent vulnerabilities
    if (input.matches("[a-zA-Z0-9]*")) {
        // Only allow alphanumeric characters to prevent injection attacks
        System.out.println("User input: " + input);
        // Further processing with validated input
        executeCommand(input);
    } else {
        // Handle invalid input appropriately
        System.out.println("Invalid input detected.");
    }
}

public void executeCommand(String command) {
    // Validate command before execution to prevent vulnerabilities
    if (command.matches("[a-zA-Z0-9\\s]*")) {
        // Only allow alphanumeric characters and spaces to prevent injection attacks
        Runtime.getRuntime().exec(command);
    } else {
        // Handle invalid command appropriately
        System.out.println("Invalid command detected.");
    }
}
```

In the vulnerable code snippet, the `handleUserInput` method directly uses the input provided by the user without any validation, making it susceptible to injection attacks. The `executeCommand` method also executes commands without validating them, which can lead to security vulnerabilities if an attacker crafts malicious input.

The good code snippet addresses these vulnerabilities by implementing input validation. The `handleUserInput` method checks if the input contains only alphanumeric characters, preventing injection attacks. Similarly, the `executeCommand` method validates the command against a pattern that allows only alphanumeric characters and spaces, ensuring that only safe commands are executed. This approach significantly reduces the risk of vulnerabilities in the web application.
